                <p><label type="entry">STATES OF THE CHURCH, or <hi rend="smallcaps">Papal
                    States</hi></label> (Ital.</p>
                <p><hi rend="italic">Stato della Chiesa, Stato Pontificio, Stato Romano, Stato
                    Ecclesiastico</hi>; Fr. <hi rend="italic">États de l'Église, Pontificat
                    Souverain de Rome,</hi> &amp;c.; Germ. <hi rend="italic">Kirchenstaat;</hi> in
                    ecclesiastical Latin often <hi rend="italic">Patrimonium Sancti Petri),</hi>
                    that portion of central Italy which, previous to the unification of the kingdom,
                    was under the direct government of the see of Rome. The territory stood at the
                    close as in the annexed table.</p>
                <p>With the exception of Benevento, surrounded by the Neapolitan province of
                    Principato Ulteriore, and the small state of Pontecorvo, enclosed within the
                    Terra di Lavoro, the States of the Church formed a compact territory, bounded on
                    the N.W. by the Lombardo-Venetian kingdom, on the N.E. by the Adriatic, on the
                    S.E. by the kingdom of Naples, on the S.W. by the Mediterranean, and on the W.
